<DOC><DOCNO> AP881220-0026 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-88 0222EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     12-20 0389</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,390</SECOND><HEAD>U.S. Court Says Federal Union Presidents Legally Supported Mondale</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A court has reversed the last of thedisciplinary suspensions against the presidents of federal employeeunions for actively supporting Democrat Walter Mondale in the 1984presidential campaign.   The ruling by the Second Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals in NewYork vacates charges brought in 1985 by the Merit Systems ProtectionBoard against Vincent R. Sombrotto, president of the NationalAssociation of Letter Carriers, and Moe Biller, president of theAmerican Postal Workers Union.   After a series of hearings, the board in 1987 ordered Sombrotto,Biller and Kenneth Blaylock, former president of the AmericanFederation of Government Employees, suspended from their governmentjobs for 60 days under the 1939 Hatch Act.   The 1939 law forbids government workers from taking ``an activepart in political management or political campaigns.''</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Reagan Reportedly May Sit on Board of L.A. Dodgers</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The White House says it is too soon to saywhether President Reagan will join the board of directors of the LosAngeles Dodgers, as reported by a sports publication.   ``He has not considered any post-presidential matters and willnot until after January 20,'' White House assistant press secretaryMark Weinberg said Monday.   The report in Sports, inc., the sports business weekly, quotedPeter O'Malley, president of the Dodgers, as saying there had beenno formal discussions with Reagan but ``quite frankly, the idea doesappeal to me.''   Reagan's first job in radio involved broadcasting re-creations ofbaseball games from wire reports.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Government Gives $91 Million to California Sandamp;L to Save Two Ohio</HEAD><TEXT>   Thrifts</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The federal government is contributing $91million to an Oakland, Calif, savings institution to rescue two OhioSandamp;Ls.   The Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., which insuresdeposits up to $100,000 in the nation's 3,000 Sandamp;Ls, is providingGolden West Financial Corp. the money in cash, regulators saidMonday. It also is purchasing bad loans of the failed institutionsfor $29 million and guaranteeing Golden West against some futureloss.   The FSLIC is receiving back 75 percent of the gains on some ofthe loans owned by the failed institutions _ Ohio Valley Savings andLoan Association, Steubenville, and First Border Savings Bank ofPiqua, which have $318 million in combined assets.</TEXT></DOC>